<author><name><![CDATA[NickH]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-08-01T13:34:16+01:00</updated>
<id>http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=44&amp;p=188#p188</id>
<link href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=44&amp;p=188#p188"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[The Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years • Frontlines - August 2011]]></title>

<category term="The Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years" scheme="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewforum.php?f=2" label="The Your Sinclair Rock'n'Roll Years"/>
<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=44&amp;p=188#p188"><![CDATA[
It's August, which means it's officially summer. As I live at the crap end of the country (weather-wise), I'm looking out of the window at a very dark sky whilst listening to Test Match Special. It's lunch time and I need to turn a light on. Joy...<br /><br /><span style="font-style: italic">Anyway...</span> When I'm not caught up in Real Life Stuff, <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=flVY6I41W2c" class="postlink">creating a two-minute advert for the site relaunch</a> or writing silly scripts such as <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=05Vh77qLMic" class="postlink">one which collected together a bunch of animated loading screen reveals</a>, I still dip my toe into researching for the <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/tvprog/" class="postlink">documentary</a>. Occasionally I get fresh insights into the goings on in the industry, and recently had a bit of a revelation about the infamous magazine Cover Tape Wars.<br /><br />As the documentary is up to 1990, you should know the story so far. You haven't seen the videos? Boy are you in for a treat - go <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/tvprog/downloads.htm" class="postlink">watch them now</a> and we'll still be here twiddling our thumbs when you get back. Twiddle, twiddle, twiddle. Right. Back? Good. As you saw, all three major Speccy mags now have monthly cover tapes, and CRASH  is pamphletized as they went all-in by stuffing their tape with re-releases at the expense of having a magazine with actual pages with actual articles in. I've <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=20" class="postlink">commented on this</a> a few times, so I'll bypass the rant and go straight on to 1991.<br /><br />Of course, Your Sinclair and Sinclair User were rereleasing the odd game on their cover tapes, but when SU announced it was considering going down the CRASH route and beefing up their cover tape with more rereleases at the expense of shrinking the magazine due to having little new to write about, industry body ELSPA cleared their throat and complained. Reading the SU letters pages reveals that a little more went on behind the scenes. ELSPA not only complained, they also blackmailed the magazines to their way of thinking: cut down on the number of rereleases or we'll cut down on the amount of advertising from our members (pretty much every software house) - and, acknowledging that their advertising had gone down recently, they also dangled the carrot of <span style="font-style: italic">extra</span> advertising if the mags played ball.<br /><br />YS was pretty quiet on this whole episode, preferring backroom diplomacy to SU's swaggering, so they quietly complied. SU also complied, but then complained in their letters pages when the extra advertising wasn't forthcoming, implying that ELSPA had stiffed them - after all, SU was ready to switch to the pamphletized format and only backed away from doing so when ELSPA started clearing their throat. For CRASH, though, ELSPA's demands were devastating to their two-year-old strategy of shrinking their mag in order to cram more games onto their tapes. All this time I thought that their 1991 return to the traditional magazine format was due to poor sales and a last-ditch change in strategy to save the magazine, but the timing now strongly indicates that they only did this to appease ELSPA as CRASH was scrambling for advert revenue, even offering low enough rates to justify labels taking out full-page ads for <span style="font-style: italic">budget</span> games.<br /><br />I was extraordinarily happy when I bought the first full-sized issue of CRASH magazine back in 1991, but the realization that they made the change before they were forced to rather than because they wanted to has taken the shine off of it a little. However it does add a little more colour to the history of the Cover Tape Wars, and is one of those stories which can only be hinted at in the documentary due to the lack of time to cover much in the way of detail.<br /><br />===== [ NEWS ] =====<br /><br />The fancy header is here for keeps <img src="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/images/smilies/icon_e_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /> I'm going to have to create some sort of supplement to the documentary which covers tape/disk-zines as there was plenty of good stuff on publications such as Enigma Tape Magazine and FRED diskzine. Yet another thing to delay until the main documentary is finished. As ever, if you would like your project covered in the News section, <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/email.htm" class="postlink">email me</a> and I'll put it into the next Frontlines.<br /><br />== [ JET PAC BOOSTED ] ==<br /><br />There's a fun-looking project being worked on in <a href="http://www.worldofspectrum.org/forums/showthread.php?t=29981" class="postlink">the World of Spectrum Forums</a> where &quot;Whizzbang&quot; and &quot;Bad Beard&quot; have come up with an editor for the classic Ultimate game Jet Pac, naming it <a href="http://goodwiigames2.blogspot.com/2011/07/jet-pac-advanced.html" class="postlink">Jet Pac Advanced</a>. As WoS is sensitive about copyrights, and Ultimate has declined WoS's request to host their games in their archive, the modification is only available as a <a href="http://nugget.no-ip.biz/spectrum/JetpacAdvancedAYInstaller.sna" class="postlink">POKE loader</a> - just like old days days when we used to have to type in hacks which would be run before loading in the actual game in order to get infinite lives. Nice work - we need more modified games as they add another dimension to the classics.<br /><br />== [ LOOK MA, NO WIRES! ] ==<br /><br />Here's a fun homebrew project: create your own wireless USB Spectrum rubber keyboard to use with emulators. Sami Vehmaa has a <a href="http://www.vehmaa.se/swezxdiy/Swedish_ZX_Spectrum_DIY_site/ZXBT.html" class="postlink">webpage</a> how he created it, complete with instructions and rather fun <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OwD4ueCyVj0" class="postlink">YouTube demo video</a>. Elite Systems are rumoured to be working on something similar with Bluetooth to tie in with their iPhone Speccy game compilations - more news on that as I get it.<br /><br />== [ ZX81 NOW 30 YEARS OLD ] ==<br /><br />The thirtieth birthday of the original ZX81 is being marked by the <a href="http://www.zx81museum.net/" class="postlink">ZX81 Museum</a> with the launch of a <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/ZX81Museum" class="postlink">YouTube Channel</a>, which goes alongside their <a href="http://twitter.com/ZX81Museum" class="postlink">Twitter feed</a> and <a href="http://www.zx81museum.net/ZXAT1/newsletter.html" class="postlink">ZXAT1 newsletter</a>. There's still new software and hardware being made for the old machine, including the ZXpand, which is a combined 32K RAM pack and SD memory card reader.<br /><br />== [ ZX81 MUSIC VIDEO ] ==<br /><br />Talking of the ZX81, YouTube user <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/soundhog09" class="postlink">soundhog09</a> has recovered a fine oddity. Back in 1983, Chris Sievey (AKA Frank Sidebottom) released a single on 7&quot; vinyl which contained a song called &quot;Camouflage&quot;. Side B contained audio tracks you could load directly into your ZX81 for four programs, one of which you meant to run in tandem with the song and acted as a music video. It's remained lost and forgotten... <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8u9ZyV-BHFA" class="postlink">until now - watch it on YouTube</a> in a video which uses the song as the soundtrack. Don't expect Pixar, but it's a nice novelty.<br /><br />== [ TWITTER FUN ] == <br /><br />Had a bit of fun on Twitter the other day by creating the #improve80sgametitlesbyaddinginmypants on a slow day. Quite a few people joined in with: Incredible Shrinking Fireman In My Pants, Chubby Gristle In My Pants, Granny's Garden In My Pants, Rolling Thunder In My Pants, Where In The World Is Carmen Sandiego? In My Pants, … you get the idea. Makes you proud to be British <img src="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/images/smilies/icon_e_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br />== [ SPECCY MEMORIES ] ==<br /><br />jdanddiet (really someone quite famous, who I'm not sure has been &quot;outed&quot; yet, so I'll stay schtumn) has written a series on <a href="http://www.retrofusion.org.uk/" class="postlink">Retro Fusion</a> about <a href="http://www.retrofusion.org.uk/blog/35/spectrum-memories-part-1/" class="postlink">his own Speccy memories</a> - there's multiple parts to it and is rather fun to dip into.<br /><br />== [ YOUR COMPUTER - NO, NOT <span style="font-style: italic">YOUR</span> COMPUTER, YOUR COMPUTER ] ==<br /><br />It's been a while since you heard about new magazine archivists - whilst World Of Spectrum add page image scans of the full runs of <a href="ftp://ftp.worldofspectrum.org/pub/sinclair/magazines/ACE/" class="postlink">ACE</a> and <a href="ftp://ftp.worldofspectrum.org/pub/sinclair/magazines/PopularComputingWeekly/" class="postlink">Popular Computing Weekly</a> to its archive, few people are willing to tackle the mountain of OCR'ing that comes with transferring these to web pages. Meurglys68 has decided to tackle a <a href="http://yourcomputeronline.wordpress.com" class="postlink">Your Computer online archive</a>, and is already up to August 1982 - &quot;only five more years to go&quot;, he tells me. Keep at it, mate, it's surprisingly satisfying after such a long slog. Some of the latest articles to be added are <a href="http://yourcomputeronline.wordpress.com/2011/04/25/graphics-spectrum-hue-and-cry/" class="postlink">one on the Spectrum's sound and graphics capabilities</a>, plus <a href="http://yourcomputeronline.wordpress.com/2011/06/12/ecological-modelling/" class="postlink">an ecological modeller for the ZX81</a>, and <a href="http://yourcomputeronline.wordpress.com/2011/03/20/review-sinclair-zx-spectrum/" class="postlink">Tim Hartnell's review of the Sinclair Spectrum</a>.<br /><br />== [ PORTABLE CRASH - MIND HOW YOU GO NOW ] ==<br /><br />Matthew Wilson (yes, this time <span style="font-style: italic">really</span> Matthew Wilson!) is experimenting with putting his <a href="http://www.crashonline.org.uk/" class="postlink">CRASH Online</a> website onto the Kindle - it's a mouth-watering idea which has got me thinking! He has a <a href="http://www.crashonline.org.uk/13/crash13.mobi" class="postlink">MOBI file for issue</a> 13 to download as an experiment, and <a href="http://www.crashonline.org.uk/13/kindle/index.htm" class="postlink">some screenshots</a> for you view if you haven't got an eBook reader.<br /><br />== [ AND ON THE YSRnRY FORUMS... ] ==<br /><br />The <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/" class="postlink">fledgling forums</a> has had a fun month, highlights being <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?f=6&amp;t=28" class="postlink">&quot;What we had to put up with!&quot;</a>, <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?f=5&amp;t=22" class="postlink">&quot;The tail-enders&quot;</a>,  <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?f=5&amp;t=27" class="postlink">&quot;Biggest Anti-Climax&quot;</a>, <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?f=8&amp;t=25" class="postlink">&quot;Time to feel old!&quot;</a>, plus <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?f=8&amp;t=20" class="postlink">&quot;Hamleys catalogue from Xmas 1983&quot;</a>. Sign up and join in for free - you don't have to be techy to enjoy it, you just have to have a love for Sinclair and SAM stuff.<br /><br />== [ GOT NEWS? EMAIL US! ] ==<br /><br />And that's it for the August Frontlines. If you have any news for the next one (start of August),  <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/email.htm" class="postlink">email me</a> and I'll put it in.<br /><br />== [ BACK ISSUES ] ==<br /><br />Collect all <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="font-style: italic">one</span></span> back issues of Frontlines <img src="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/images/smilies/icon_e_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /> <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?f=2&amp;t=24" class="postlink">July 2011</a> is still available.<br /><br />== [ STANDARD FRONTLINES URL ] ==<br /><br />Bookmark <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/frontlines/">http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/frontlines/</a><!-- m --> and check in the first week of every month for the latest issue of Frontlines.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=54">NickH</a> — Mon Aug 01, 2011 1:34 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
