<div class="ca-bbcode"><div class="ca-bbcode2 ca-quote"><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />I remember the days of Program Power in YS - four or five pages of hex dumps! I did occasionally type in the smaller hex dumps, such as their character set searcher which to this day I remember typing in during the scorching summer of '89. As for their full games, I only ever typed in The Trainspotter Game YS published in BASIC in 1986.<br /><br />Hmmm... I should probably cross-reference the YS issue pages with Jim Grimwood's excellent Type Fantastic was contains all these listings as (corrected!) downloads.<br /></div></blockquote></div></div><br /><br />I think that most of the type-ins are/were a disappointment. Several hours of entering code, followed by several more debugging the things only to find out that you hadn't typed in <span style="font-style: italic">Atic Atac</span> but were instead left with a jerky, audio-visual mess.  That said, my fascination stems from first seeing <span style="font-style: italic">Pong</span> (on the Grandstand, I think), and wondering 'how does the television a) make the bats and ball move, and b)how does it know to make the ball go backwards once it has hit a bat'.<br /><br />Program Power was exceptional in the quality of the listings being published. Generally these were a cut above the average on offer elsewhere, although even here the listings were plagued with typos and/or printing problems.  <br /><br />The Type Fantastic is a wonderful site (although nowhere near as good as YSRNY obviously!).  I have even contributed a couple of ZX-81 listings myself.  <br /><br />Undoubtedly, <span style="font-style: italic">Jet Set Willy</span>, <span style="font-style: italic">Knightlore</span> and such like are what the Speccy should be remembered for, but the whole 'type in' scenario is an important, fascinating and rarely mentioned aspect of early gaming and computer use.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=77">Meurglys68</a> — Wed Jul 27, 2011 3:49 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
