<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=41&amp;p=175#p175"><![CDATA[
You may think you’ve never heard of quadrature amplification modulation (QAM), but you’ve almost certainly heard it. QAM is a method of sending digital data over an analogue channel. It combines frequency (pitch) changes with amplitude (loudness) and phase changes. It’s the noise you hear from a fax machine, an old modem or a game loading on a Spectrum. QAM is also the basis of signalling in DSL and cable modems.<br /><br /><br />Just one of a hundred world-changing technologies listed by PCPro staff.<br /><br /><a href="http://www.pcpro.co.uk/features/368716/100-technologies-that-changed-the-world" class="postlink">http://www.pcpro.co.uk/features/368716/100-technologies-that-changed-the-world</a><br /><br />Nice concise explanations and I learned a thing or two.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=69">warmtoffee</a> — Sun Jul 24, 2011 11:22 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
